<br>
I just spent the last three days (THREE DAYS!  not six hours!) in Blackburrow collecting Blackburrow Casks for the Cloak of Jaggedpine quest.  I even gave the second one I found away to Chase, who had two and needed his third to get the Cloak, setting me back another day it turns out.  I swam, I (the player) read for my PhD exams (got half a book read between Gnoll Brewers), sitting on the boulder right by the Razorgill place, helping out lower-level characters if they got in trouble near where I was sitting vigil (or practicing swimming--moved up 70 points in that time).<br>
<br>
I was expecting to have to wait at this site, too, probably as long as I spent in that bottom level of Blackburrow, but when I got there, Dyllin was up.  I was phenomenally lucky in that, and I don't deny that.  I had no prior knowledge that he was there or would be at that time.  I was just checking in--and for the first time--and &quot;beginner's luck&quot; struck.  Sometimes, people get lucky.  That's part of the game.  In retrospect, I should not have looked that gifthorse in the mouth; I should have just taken my stuff and moved on.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry the Order of the Oaken's guildmembers failed to complete this quest at the appropriate level to do it, but I am the appropriate level to do it and I can also use the item.  I do not see the Trivial Loot Code as a justification for farming any item.  Yes, it's fine to send lower level guildmembers to get the item--but once they've gotten it, they need to let others have a turn at it.  The Order of the Oaken's guildmembers that I encountered there (and there were at least five), with the exception of Krystallgold, refused to let me have a turn.<br>
<br>
I gave them the page as a gesture signalling that I was willing to wait my turn and, yes, wait six hours for him to pop back up.  It's too bad they weren't willing to give me a turn until Krystallgold intervened.<br>
<br>
I maintained here, as I maintained with them, that all I wanted was either my page back or another shot at Dyllin and an apology for the deception.<br>
